    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with feline asthma</h2>
      <p>Feline asthma is manageable for most cats — with the right treatment and trigger management, many cats have infrequent episodes and a good quality of daily life. The challenge is that asthma overlaps significantly with other respiratory conditions, including heart disease, which have very different treatments. Getting the diagnosis right before committing to long-term management matters.</p>
      <p>Artie had asthma alongside FIV, hyperthyroidism, and the neurological symptoms that ultimately ended his life. Managing his asthma was complicated by the interaction with his other conditions — some medications that help asthma carry additional risks for FIV-positive cats or diabetic cats, and the relationship between respiratory distress and his neurological decline was difficult to untangle.</p>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Open-mouth breathing or blue gums in a cat is always a medical emergency.</strong> Do not wait. Go to an emergency vet immediately.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask whether heart disease has been ruled out.</strong> Both conditions can cause breathing difficulty and coughing, but the treatments are different — and steroids that help asthma can worsen heart failure. Before starting steroids for presumed asthma, confirm that cardiac causes have been excluded.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about inhaled treatment over oral or injectable.</strong> Inhaled steroids deliver medication directly to the lungs with fewer systemic effects. For cats who will be on long-term treatment, or who have other conditions that make systemic steroids riskier, this is worth asking about specifically.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about a rescue bronchodilator for home use.</strong> For cats with episodic asthma, having a bronchodilator on hand for acute episodes can be important. Make sure you know whether this is appropriate for your cat and how to use it.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about environmental triggers.</strong> Scented products, dusty litters, and smoke are common triggers. Before escalating treatment, it is worth asking whether there are environmental changes that could reduce frequency of episodes.</li>
        <li><strong>If your cat has other conditions, name them when discussing asthma treatment.</strong> Systemic steroid risks are different for an FIV-positive cat, a diabetic cat, or a cat with heart disease. The treatment choice needs to account for the whole picture.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

